L59: ## Paragraphs
L60: 
L61: A paragraph (from the Greek paragraphos, “to write beside” or “written beside”) 
L62: is a self-contained unit of a discourse in writing dealing with a particular 
L63: point or idea. A paragraph consists of one or more sentences. Though not 
L64: required by the syntax of any language, paragraphs are usually an expected part 
L65: of formal writing, used to organize longer prose.
L66: 
L67: [Top]

L69: ## Blockquotes
L70: 
L71: > A block quotation (also known as a long quotation or extract) is a quotation 
L72: in a written document, that is set off from the main text as a paragraph, or 
L73: block of text.
L74: > 
L75: > It is typically distinguished visually using indentation and a different 
L76: typeface or smaller size quotation. It may or may not include a citation, 
L77: usually placed at the bottom.
L78: > 
L79: > Said no one, ever.
